# **05  Unit economics**

| **Metric** | **MVP phase** | **Phase 1.5** | **Year 2 target** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **CAC (Customer Acquisition Cost)** | ₹0 (organic only) | ₹50–150 (referral + light paid) | ₹100–300 (paid mix) |
| **ARPU (Average Revenue Per User — paying)** | — | ₹108/month (blended ₹99 + ₹149) | ₹115/month (Premium Plus mix increasing) |
| **LTV estimate (12-month)** | — | ₹900–1,100 (avg 8–10 months paid) | ₹1,200–1,500 (as retention improves) |
| **LTV:CAC ratio** | — | 6:1–22:1 | 4:1–15:1 (as CAC rises with paid) |
| **Payback period** | — | < 2 months | 2–3 months |
| **Gross margin (subscription)** | — | ~85% (infrastructure stays on free tiers) | ~80% (infrastructure costs rise with scale) |
| **Ad revenue per free user** | — | ₹8–15/month (Indian CPM rates) | ₹12–20/month |

| **Key insight on CAC: **During the MVP and Phase 0.5, CAC is effectively ₹0 because all users come through personal referral and organic channels. The referral programme (when F-50 activates) keeps CAC below ₹150 for a long time because the reward is premium days, not cash. This is the most capital-efficient acquisition model available for a consumer app in India. |
